cores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.75,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.87,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"Cyanosulfidic phosphoro-Strecker route closely follows Patel et al. 2015 (Nature Chemistry). The one-pot \u03b1-APN formation at ~70% yield from acetaldehyde under phosphoro-Strecker conditions is well-supported. Pathway is shorter than P1 by bypassing the explicit imine step. Shares the rxn_004 weakness with P1. Overall a strong, literature-grounded route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify Cu(I)/Cu(II) photoredox cycling and phosphate buffer conditions for rxn_010 to better match Patel et al. 2015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.86,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.88,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n      \"feedback\": \"Bucherer-Bergs pathway via hydantoin intermediate is well-supported by Pulletikurti et al. 2022 (Nature Chemistry). The 5-methylhydantoin intermediate is chemically plausible and provides an alternative hydrolysis route avoiding direct aminonitrile hydrolysis. The decarbamoylation step (rxn_015) at 80\u00b0C is reasonable. Nice integration of CO\u2082 capture into the hydantoin ring. The pathway also elegantly links to pyrimidine synthesis per literature.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider specifying the 80\u00b0C condition for rxn_015 explicitly; note the connection to dihydroorotate synthesis as per Pulletikurti et al.\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_016\": 0.87\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.82,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.90,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.87,\n      \"feedback\": \"Shortest pathway: direct CO\u2082 reduction to pyruvate (Beyazay et al. 2023) followed by reductive amination on iron oxyhydroxides (Barge et al. 2019). Both steps are experimentally demonstrated with specific mineral catalysts. The pathway is entirely hydrothermal, which means no environmental progression to surface, but this is chemically justified for alkaline vent chemistry. The 1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) requirement for rxn_016 is well-documented. Yields of 0.1\u20135% are realistic.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify the 1:1 Fe(II):Fe(III) ratio and pH 9 conditions for rxn_016 for full Barge et al. alignment\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.85\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.87,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.80,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.88,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n      \"feedback\": \"Parallel to P4 but uses Ni catalysis with H\u2082 gas (Kaur et al. 2024, Chem). The 5 bar H\u2082 pressure at 22\u00b0C and pH 7\u20138 is somewhat unusual for a hydrothermal label\u2014these are more moderate conditions. Nevertheless, both steps are experimentally validated. The pathway closely parallels modern enzymatic transamination, supporting the proto-metabolic hypothesis.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Consider whether the 22\u00b0C/5 bar H\u2082 conditions are better labeled as 'Surface' or specify that these conditions can also occur in low-temperature hydrothermal settings\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.78\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.80,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.78,\n      \"feedback\": \"HCN oligomerization and hydrolysis (Or\u00f3 1961, Ferris et al. 1978) is a well-known route but less selective\u2014the polymer produces many amino acids and other products. Alanine yields from HCN polymer are modest and variable. The concentration requirement (>0.01 M HCN) is a significant constraint, though eutectic freezing can address this. The pathway is short and valid but less controlled than Strecker routes.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_019\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify HCN concentration requirements and hydrolysis conditions (acid vs base); consider adding eutectic freezing as a concentration mechanism; note that this produces a complex mixture, not selective alanine synthesis\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.90,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.90\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.88,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.90,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.92,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.92,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.90,\n      \"feedback\": \"Excellent pathway combining Fischer-Tropsch-type hydrothermal chemistry (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user 2006) with the classic Strecker sequence. The CO\u2082\u2192CO\u2192acetaldehyde hydrothermal entry followed by surface Strecker synthesis represents an ideal hydrothermal\u2192surface environmental flow. All individual steps are well-supported experimentally. This is one of the strongest and most literature-aligned pathways in the network.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Could specify Fe/Ni sulfide mineral types and temperature range (80\u2013120\u00b0C) for FTT steps\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_021\": 0.80,\n        \"rxn_022\": 0.83,\n        \"rxn_020\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.82,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.84,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.85,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.83,\n      \"feedback\": \"Serine decarboxylation pathway is well-supported by Chandru et al. 2013, who showed alanine enrichment at hydrothermal temperatures from serine decomposition. The formose reaction step (rxn_021) is known to be problematic without borate or other stabilizers\u2014formaldehyde tends to produce complex sugar mixtures. The Strecker synthesis of serine from glycolaldehyde (rxn_022) is standard. Overall a viable but less efficient route that importantly captures the hydrothermal enrichment phenomenon.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_021\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Specify borate mineral stabilization for formose reaction to favor glycolaldehyde over complex sugars; note that this pathway's main prebiotic relevance is the hydrothermal enrichment of alanine from other amino acids\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_023\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_014\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.83\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.84,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n 